        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How is cost per unit calculated in an auto component plant?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Add direct material, direct labour and absorbed factory overhead, then divide by the good units produced. A press shop consuming Rs 18 lakh of steel, Rs 4 lakh of labour and Rs 8 lakh of overhead for 60,000 accepted pieces has a cost of Rs 50 a piece. Rejection and rework must be loaded on to good units rather than ignored."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between standard cost and actual cost in a plant?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Standard cost is the predetermined cost per unit used for planning and inventory valuation, while actual cost is what was really spent, and the gap between them is a variance. If the standard steel rate is Rs 55 per kilogram and the mill invoices Rs 58, a 10,000 kilogram issue throws up an adverse price variance of Rs 30,000."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How is scrap sold from a manufacturing plant taxed and costed?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Scrap sale is a taxable supply, with iron and steel scrap under HSN 7204 attracting 18 percent GST, and the seller also collects TCS at 1 percent under Section 206C(1) of the Income Tax Act. In the cost sheet the scrap realisation is credited against the cost of production, so a plant that ignores scrap recovery overstates its cost per unit."
          }
        }
      ]
